article.headline: Jackson, Lawson help Lady Vols remain unbeaten in SEC
article.linkText: Third-ranked Lady Vols have little trouble against Florida
article.story:
KNOXVILLE, Tenn. (AP) --  Tennessee coach Pat Summitt's sympathy
for a friend coaching a struggling team can only go so far.

	   Gwen Jackson scored 18 points and Kara Lawson added 13 points
and 12 rebounds as the third-ranked Lady Vols were never challenged
in a 79-40 win over Florida on Sunday.

	   Carolyn Peck, a former assistant under Summitt, returned to
Knoxville as the first-year coach of the Lady Gators for the first
time.

	   "What would you've suggested I do?'' Summitt said when asked if
she felt bad for Peck's team. "Obviously Coach Peck is a great
coach and a friend of mine. You do feel for them. They have a young
team. I'm confident they'll get the job done there.''

	   Tennessee (20-3, 9-0 Southeastern Conference) had an even easier
time than last month's 94-53 win over the Lady Gators (8-13, 0-8)
in Gainesville, Fla., demonstrating the vast difference between the
league's top and bottom teams.

	   Tennessee had little trouble winning its 11th straight game
since last month's loss to Connecticut and 45th in a row over an SEC opponent at home.

	   The Lady Vols jumped out to an 18-4 lead before Florida made its
second field goal of the game.

	   Tennessee, which led by 17 at halftime, started the second half
with two steals and three baskets in transition. Jackson scored
eight points in a 15-0 run in the first 4:50 of the second half.

	   Florida, which shot a season-low 21 percent from the floor and
scored the fewest points this season, turned the ball over five
times in the span and didn't score a field goal in the second half
until Vanessa Hayden's basket with 12:56 left. Lawson and Jackson had gone to the bench by then.

	   Brittany Davis led Florida with 10 points.

	   Despite the lopsided score, Peck was pleased with her team.

	   "My team had the confidence and courage and heart to go out and
compete. That's a good thing,'' she said. "The last time we played
Tennessee we gave up 95 points and that was on our own court. Our defense was a lot better.''

	   The Lady Gators tried to make the score close but couldn't trim
it to below 12 in the first half despite outrebounding Tennessee
27-25.

	   Florida, however, couldn't take advantage of getting more
rebounds as it shot 7-of-35 in the first half.

	   Peck started four freshmen and Hayden, a junior. Five freshmen
had started the previous three games.

	   Peck was warmly welcomed by the partisan crowd. The fans showed
surprise when referee June Courteau whistled Peck for a technical
foul after arguing a call.

	   Peck became the only former Lady Vols coach, assistant or
player-turned-coach to beat Summitt when she coached Purdue to a
win over Tennessee in 1998.

	   On Saturday, she wasn't looking for sympathy.

	   "There are few coaches who walk into a program and make it
work. If it were easy, everyone would do it,'' she said. "These
kids are special because they've taken on a huge challenge. They
are just going to get better and better. I'm encouraged.''

	   The Lady Vols had six steals in the first half and forced 11
turnovers, getting easy baskets in transition.

	   They also had seven blocks before halftime. In one play, LaToya
Davis swatted Kelly Stevenson's 3-point attempt. Lawson caught the
loose ball and passed it ahead to Davis, who was racing toward the
basket at the other end. Davis scored on the driving layup as the
Lady Vols pushed their lead to 38-18 with 1:08 left before
halftime.
